Cell["Setting the Stage: How This Notebook Flows", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a098b720-7ee6-4876-8f04-5b910470f7c9"],

Cell["\<\
This notebook is a computation-first tour of the single qubit, how a \
two-dimensional Hilbert space description (kets, bras, inner products) turns \
into the geometric Bloch ball, how measurements (Born rule, eigenbases, \
projectors) read probabilities directly from amplitudes, why density matrices \
are required to describe ensembles and mixedness (purity, von Neumann \
entropy), and how unitary dynamics and spinors live in SU(2) while their \
visible action on the Bloch vector is an SO(3) rotation. Along the way, we \
build the Pauli operator toolkit explicitly, Hermiticity, \
commutators/anticommutators, Levi\[Dash]Civita structure, Pauli product \
identities, closed-form exponentials, dynamical equation, collapse of the \
state during measurment and more, so that every abstract statement is \
immediately testable computationally and every result can be interpreted both \
algebraically and geometrically.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3ad4d4cb-dc08-4149-a1ac-c12502931782"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In other words, I\[CloseCurlyQuote]ve tried to build a catalogue of \
computational experiments on single qubits, tools and examples that help you \
run experiments computationally and learn directly from what you observe. I \
strongly believe in a computation-first narrative for learning: in a sense, \
if I cannot compute it, I cannot claim to understand it. This echoes a very \
",
 ButtonBox["Feynman-y idea",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://digital.archives.caltech.edu/collections/Images/1.10-29/"], 
    None}],
 ": real understanding shows up when you can do the thing, derive it, predict \
it, simulate it, estimate it, rather than just repeat/read words."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"74604c3d-1709-4395-a808-42f353325825"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Before we start, pay attention to a few things. The environment you see is \
a ",
 ButtonBox["Wolfram (Mathematica) notebook",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.wolfram.com/notebooks/"], None}],
 ". Wolfram notebooks consist of ",
 ButtonBox["sequences of cells",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/tutorial/WorkingWithCells.\
html"], None}],
 ". Look at the right side of this notebook and you can see cell brakets. \
This notebook is written so that you should evaluate the cells from top to \
bottom. Although I did my best to make the input cells independent, there are \
still variables that are defined in earlier cells and used later, meaning \
some cells depend on previous ones. You should be mindful of these \
dependencies when evaluating the notebook."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"de0c7653-7c98-46d0-819a-375c6d04f4b8"],

Cell["\<\
Additionally, the story is presented as a continuous sequence, like a movie. \
I have added a few headings to help with transitions from one topic to \
another, but I have avoided breaking the narrative into rigid sections. \
Sometimes a feature or property is introduced and used before we explain why \
it applies or unpack the underlying mathematical details. This is \
intentional, because in this notebook the ability to apply an idea often \
matters more than following an abstract proof first. Overall, the rhythm is: \
concept \[RightArrow] computation \[RightArrow] interpretation.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a77e87a4-24d8-4c93-9722-9f7ba948ff78"],

Cell["\<\
Inevitably, some of the code in this notebook will look complicated at first. \
My suggestion is to focus on the output and its meaning before worrying about \
every detail of the input code. Once you understand what a piece of code is \
doing conceptually, then go back and unpack how it is written.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8b8a59d4-788a-4530-a2bd-b47a316c3b62"],

Cell["\<\
Remember that you are not locked into the code as given. You can (and should) \
modify it, try your own variations, and run your own numerical experiments. \
Almost every line in this notebook could be written in several different \
ways, and exploring those alternatives is one of the best ways to learn.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4fda9a0c-1fe8-444d-9963-fb6a2deaa51f"],

Cell["\<\
One of the strengths of the Wolfram Mathematica notebook environment is \
precisely this interactive, exploratory style. If you are using the cloud \
version, you can click \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Make Your Own Copy\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] to duplicate the notebook and edit it freely. If you \
are working locally, save your own version and experiment with it. The \
notebook interface is a powerful medium for computational thinking and \
simulation; it is worth taking the time to get comfortable with it and really \
use it as a laboratory for your ideas.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f883015a-e1e4-4a8b-aa0a-56ee0ada670a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If you have any suggestions or questions, please reach out to us at ",
 ButtonBox["quantum@wolfram.com",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["mailto:quantum@wolfram.com"], None}]
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"70bedf32-7d9d-4ccf-9acc-956e8c6a55ea"],

Cell["Prerequisites and How to Read This", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"26b3c866-6b5f-4775-b0a8-2f23287991ef"],

Cell["\<\
This tour is self-contained but moves quickly. To follow the computations \
comfortably you should be at ease with complex numbers and basic linear \
algebra (vectors, matrices, eigenvalues and eigenvectors, and the matrix \
exponential); a little group-theory vocabulary is introduced as needed. Parts \
I through III need nothing beyond that.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e11824cd-2ca7-406b-b664-6f1fbc8209ac"],

Cell["\<\
Part IV additionally leans on elementary stochastic calculus (Wiener \
processes, the It\[OHat]-versus-Stratonovich distinction, It\[OHat]'s lemma, \
and martingales). These are built up from the ground via the \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]drunken sailor\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] random walk, so \
no prior exposure is strictly required, but the pace there is steeper.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"876b77ae-0295-475a-a297-304b09e2e836"],

Cell["\<\
The narrative reads straight through, but its real value is interactive: \
evaluate the cells from top to bottom and modify them. Some cells depend on \
variables defined earlier, so order matters.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c64191ec-b107-4fc0-bcbf-ec1ab67795dd"],

Cell["Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s start!", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"147a7ed0-4318-43eb-a8a2-a598fc94dd62"],

Cell["Part I: State Vectors and Bloch Geometry", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"69720a22-a412-49a2-b1f5-c4d8a0bf6424"],

Cell["Complex Numbers as Two Degrees of Freedom", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6880071d-1f7b-4af0-8b2d-01220ff129f2"],

Cell["\<\
The simplest quantum system we usually consider in quantum mechanics is one \
whose states live in a two-dimensional Hilbert space, what we call a single \
qubit. A Hilbert space is a complex vector space equipped with an inner \
product, and it is complete with respect to the norm induced by that inner \
product. In such a two-dimensional Hilbert space, the state of the system may \
be represented in two equivalent-looking but conceptually distinct ways: for \
an isolated system in a definite pure state, we use a normalized state vector \
(a two component complex vector); more generally\[LongDash]especially when \
describing classical uncertainty about preparation, entanglement with an \
environment, or partial information, we use a density operator/matrix (a 2\
\[Times]2 matrix), which acts on the same Hilbert space and provides the most \
general description of a qubit\[CloseCurlyQuote]s state. Whether we represent \
the qubit by a state vector or by a density matrix, the underlying objects \
are built from complex numbers.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b5e170fc-df6b-4248-a012-181fe1f679f6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A complex number can be written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "=", 
   StyleBox["x", "TI"], "+", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
   StyleBox["y", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d9eb9b70-050c-4de6-b0bf-85f79d1807c6"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["x", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fb56c8f2-0b8a-4f5d-865c-2226a8f2082d"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["y", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b347b08a-d9a8-42e9-899c-a2347b5909d2"],
 " are real numbers and i is the imaginary unit, defined by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], "2"], "=", "-", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "113575a9-c61c-4b3b-a734-09130f85cae8"],
 ". The same number can also be written in polar form as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "=", 
   StyleBox["r", "TI"], " ", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", "\[CurlyPhi]"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "48abc9e8-af1a-4c53-8d56-2c523f6d23cd"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["r", "TI"], "=", "\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[RightBracketingBar]"}]], 
  "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6dec8794-0a40-4806-b4b4-a85782480431"],
 " is the absolute value (modulus) of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7ebdb6b4-e3d2-43fd-bf22-d584fd85fb90"],
 ", and \[CurlyPhi] is its argument (angle). The complex conjugate of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3a5eeb93-e9d6-43ca-8794-fa1843d2f902"],
 ", denoted by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "*"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1be314e1-d7a9-41eb-9bfa-b8857d0b642f"],
 ", is given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["z", "TI"], "*"], "=", 
   StyleBox["x", "TI"], "-", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
   StyleBox["y", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "88cff933-3fd2-4a0a-a191-78210cbb24b0"],
 ", or equivalently ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "=", 
   StyleBox["r", "TI"], " ", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"-", 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", "\[CurlyPhi]"}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6eefa55a-a352-476e-876f-9fa2b0445d09"],
 " in polar form. In short, a complex number contains two real degrees of \
freedom."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"55ef9fbe-074e-4912-a11b-746ec36679e6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute the complex conjugate of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"3", "+", "2", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "00e6b317-4bf1-485b-a8be-af3a9681ddb4"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6015b395-0088-4ea0-ab48-7cf81bb2e588"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
  RowBox[{"3", " ", "+", " ", 
   RowBox[{"2", " ", "I"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[1]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"05a08925-c384-45c5-b77c-7a27d3dfc810"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Find ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"3", "+", "2", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4d8069c1-5fc6-4c7d-8212-7390a96a62db"],
 " in polar form:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8ea68493-0240-4b2f-aee8-8bb3d198b21d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AbsArg", "[", 
  RowBox[{"3", " ", "+", " ", 
   RowBox[{"2", " ", "I"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[2]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"13bf7774-6173-4992-b6f7-972a5c18e12f"],

Cell["\<\
Verify that the polar form is the same as the original complex number:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"58b33f3f-19df-4370-9f18-07e851f3d82e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"#1", " ", 
     RowBox[{"E", "^", 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"I", " ", "#2"}], ")"}]}]}], " ", "&"}], " ", "@@", " ", 
   RowBox[{"AbsArg", "[", 
    RowBox[{"3", " ", "+", " ", 
     RowBox[{"2", " ", "I"}]}], "]"}]}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"3", " ", "+", " ", 
   RowBox[{"2", " ", "I"}]}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[3]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"347e8738-327b-4912-b249-5e6b5e6a5de2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As said, the complex number ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"3", "+", "2", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0d47d1f5-5cd6-47e5-9ed2-78a5fec40e09"],
 " has two degrees of freedom: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "3"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"2", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e63f9fec-c5a4-454a-bf32-a04143c8343d"],
 ". Using them, one can construct the polar form of the complex number."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"aa1ef171-3ec5-40ab-a825-dd6cc99ca80f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"ToPolarCoordinates", "[", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"3", ",", " ", "2"}], "}"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[4]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"385de761-b488-4860-8913-9b12fb135fc2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Multiplication of a complex number by its complex conjugate is always a \
non-negative real number. This product is written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["z", "TI"], "*"], 
   StyleBox["z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d00f9914-10ae-412b-ab13-16f990b97709"],
 " or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], " ", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["z", "TI"], "*"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0a9c6b42-89ba-40ef-8712-e80b89d249ed"],
 ", and is usually denoted by the absolute square ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     RowBox[{
       StyleBox["z", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
    "Abs"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5061806e-d4d4-4001-ac85-5a9e2e13e138"],
 ". Given the polar form, one can write ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    TemplateBox[{
      RowBox[{
        StyleBox["z", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
     "Abs"], "2"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["r", "TI"], "2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e3482464-52d1-4528-82c7-e1454430cebf"],
 ". The usual norm of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["z", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7d717088-5df7-4d99-9f61-b0db67ac67b4"],
 " (also called the modulus) is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"\[LeftBracketingBar]", 
   StyleBox["z", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[RightBracketingBar]", "=", 
   StyleBox["r", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "32be7c73-c5d2-4d6b-9642-ffafb9154156"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"864ad4e3-202b-4985-8a56-3d8c280f6042"],

Cell["\<\
State Vectors and Normalization (Norms, Global Phase, Degrees of Freedom)\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"099c8820-5315-44f4-b559-e4af4c751099"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For a two-level quantum system (qubit), a pure state is represented (up to \
an overall complex phase such as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", "\[CurlyPhi]"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9688d9b4-045d-447a-893c-101f4117a84d"],
 ") by a two-component complex vector, usually called the state vector. For \
example, the vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1", "/", "2"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    SqrtBox["3"], "/", "2", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e227d32a-b8a0-45ea-b280-1b687c4c3290"],
 " represents a pure quantum state. We will assume that all state vectors are \
normalized, meaning that their norm is equal to 1. For a vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ac89fe2e-8589-41db-9e40-a3c825b7844c"],
 " with components ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["v", "TI"], "0"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ca82cfaf-bbdb-46e6-959d-8a8d01befe18"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "dc096889-b66a-478a-b53f-6c7332b5eb9f"],
 ", i.e. ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "0"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fb6086c6-68a9-4ffc-81d0-44e92df0e37b"],
 " , the norm is defined as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]},
    "Norm"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       OverscriptBox[
        StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "*"], ".", 
      OverscriptBox[
       StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "=", 
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       TemplateBox[{
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["v", "TI"], "0"]},
        "Abs"], "2"], "+", 
      SuperscriptBox[
       TemplateBox[{
         SubscriptBox[
          StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
        "Abs"], "2"]}]]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e8abd4b3-62fa-4334-a9f9-876248c79fdb"],
 ", where * denotes the complex conjugate and \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]\
\[CenterDot]\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] denotes the usual dot product. The \
complex conjugate of a vector is obtained by taking the complex conjugate of \
each of its components."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0d835b8c-9494-4b8d-9f97-93c27a110479"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate the complex conjugate of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1", "/", "2"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    SqrtBox["3"], "/", "2", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c4dcc406-7513-4d50-96a1-3961e1c2dfc6"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0a96fd55-e133-4775-aed4-fa320226e1b4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"I", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "3", "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "/", "2"}], "]"}]], "Input",\

 CellLabel->"In[5]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"0d7f5a25-ea0a-45f3-b5eb-42704e8e6a04"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate norm of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1", "/", "2"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    SqrtBox["3"], "/", "2", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "472d4d7b-f2f0-46c4-8d73-f5c522dadbeb"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"297b9e0e-5c5e-447e-b922-ce05504efcba"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"I", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "3", "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "/", "2"}], "]"}]], "Input",\

 CellLabel->"In[6]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"0197a17e-eff5-486b-a139-d653a61cbc55"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate norm of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1", "/", "2"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    SqrtBox["3"], "/", "2", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "570dbba2-fead-41e7-a1e4-d8858dfdd25b"],
 " explicitly as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SqrtBox[
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "*"], ".", 
    StyleBox["v", "TI"]}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "eb044442-e4c1-415e-ad4a-9175ab89f1af"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"75eca75e-9bef-45d7-8263-f2b5e9212e44"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vector", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"I", " ", 
         RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "3", "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "/", "2"}]}], "}"}], ",",
    " ", 
   RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "vector", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vector"}], 
    "]"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[7]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"e1df64da-c96b-4789-8105-4002742d779d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate norm of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4e1acebd-d6c6-4e37-a1e7-1b000c5e2c9c"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b4457829-681b-41a3-a877-046678a5b259"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[Theta]", "/", "2"}], "]"}], ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "^", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
       RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
        RowBox[{"\[Theta]", "/", "2"}], "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Theta]", " ", "|", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", 
    " ", "\n", "  ", "Reals"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[8]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"39ea527c-225c-4927-b0a4-952a8ff8dea7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate norm of the state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "475674e0-44bb-4716-8192-682f804a4373"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b144a72d-b998-43cd-a239-5a5ffa22f6b8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[9]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"0c67b949-398b-45ba-a91e-748da56766c9"],

Cell["\<\
Since the norm of a state vector is not automatically equal to one, we often \
multiply the vector by an overall (nonzero) scalar factor, typically called a \
normalization factor, to ensure the state is normalized.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3694729c-cbdf-4d92-94be-68ce43733b5b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Normalize the state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5a7ad811-ddae-45b6-80cf-d61b86f4d2f7"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d5d9cf71-f01c-406c-b20e-2fffa17d4940"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Normalize", "[", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[10]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"869965b1-b2a3-4e69-b4eb-43aac83ea2d0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the above example, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "/", 
   SqrtBox[
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["b", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["[",
        SpanMaxSize->1], 
       StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["]",
        SpanMaxSize->1]}], "2"], "+", 
     StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["b", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["[",
        SpanMaxSize->1], 
       StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["]",
        SpanMaxSize->1]}], "2"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ae9d1ee5-fd51-4043-87ca-b0aab8371367"],
 " is the normalization factor."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f1283ed4-4b49-4c7e-964a-4608b2f3fcf1"],

Cell["Verify the norm is now 1:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"917e50ea-9378-4296-b4b2-d87b08f4e455"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Norm", "@", 
   RowBox[{"Normalize", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], "]"}]}], " ", "//", 
  " ", "FullSimplify"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[11]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"950e3689-73c6-486e-9f71-3cc2abf534b4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As mentioned before, for a qubit, the state vector is represented by a \
two-component complex-valued vector, for example ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", " ", 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"]}], "}"}], "\[Element]", 
   SuperscriptBox["\:2102", "2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "028f6f46-2cd5-40f5-947a-8439c2487a27"],
 ". The numbers ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "134d3211-5983-40ec-9792-48466424a03e"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "47f2b51e-e246-4d92-b370-ed4908a2edeb"],
 " are called (probability) amplitudes. They are the coefficients of the \
basis states in the linear combination that describes the quantum \
superposition."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2477700c-dad5-4219-8462-91d319623b9e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Multiplying a state vector by an overall complex phase factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], "\[CurlyPhi]"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c9a6a8bc-871a-4eed-82ee-eb83f2af8e73"],
 " does not change the physical quantum state it represents, because all \
physical predictions (for example, measurement probabilities, which depend on \
absolute squares of amplitudes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
    "Abs"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d3a947c1-80b7-4d26-b8fc-151623b07cb5"],
 ") are unchanged by a global phase."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2881ac93-11e4-4724-9a1e-0d56a2176103"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute probabilities and verify two states ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ef44ca7d-648e-4f2c-a947-d13a0d71abfc"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], "\[CurlyPhi]"}]], "{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c71e1a8e-4089-4c6f-b174-8f6c555362ec"],
 " are physically the same:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3c80115f-cbcc-4c59-b53b-82c0758f2927"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Abs", "[", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], "]"}], "^", "2"}], 
    " ", "==", " ", "\n", "  ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Abs", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "^", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[CurlyPhi]"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], "^", 
     "2"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[CurlyPhi]", " ", "\\\n"}], "\[Element]", " ", "Reals"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[12]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"e4d898a4-db95-4e59-9340-c8738f5bb366"],

Cell["\<\
We will discuss measurement probabilities in more detail later.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"128c7c56-41cc-4bf0-a54c-55e21131ed98"],

Cell["The Most General Pure Qubit State", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"5a4de86d-66b2-4c63-853c-141d1f8a1c23"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "When we want to write a general pure state of a single qubit, we can choose \
a global phase so that the first component of the state vector is real (as if \
in the polar form, we set its argument as zero), while the second component \
may be complex. If we also require the state to be normalized, the most \
general pure qubit state can be written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "57f20207-2cc3-4444-a14f-1e3b006bfc1f"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "\[LessEqual]", "\[Pi]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e9a039c5-7555-46b7-a91d-679838776940"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
   StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], "\[LessEqual]", "2", "\[Pi]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "366737ee-69bc-401e-92c8-69da4351e498"],
 ". We will discuss the motivation to have ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5b185519-9c57-4805-becd-67012ce4ed2b"],
 " rather than ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], " "}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "06c2f6be-e163-422c-9600-5bca7f40adb8"],
 " soon when we introduce Bloch sphere. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s rephrase this \
idea differently."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9984dddd-6833-4b4e-ba07-7952c36a6c2a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The state vector of a single qubit can be written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "44886711-6005-4169-9bce-e122349c9d6b"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "\[Element]", "\:2102"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "85660145-edcd-4a07-ac1a-333fffef4d94"],
 ". This means the state is specified by two complex numbers, i.e., four real \
parameters, i.e. ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "0"]}]]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1"]}]], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a716c5f0-40bf-4494-95e7-f9559994f21b"],
 ". Imposing normalization, removes one real degree of freedom, and \
identifying state vectors that differ only by an overall complex phase \
removes another real degree of freedom. Mathematically it means: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "0"]}]]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1"]}]], "}", "\[Rule]", "1", "/", 
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0", "2"], "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1", "2"]}]], "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "0"]}]]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1"]}]], "}", "\[Rule]", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "0"]}]], "/", 
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0", "2"], "+", 
      SubsuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1", "2"]}]], "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "0"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["r", "TI"], "1"], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      StyleBox["(",
       SpanMaxSize->1], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "1"], "-", 
       SubscriptBox["\[CurlyPhi]", "0"]}], 
      StyleBox[")",
       SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "}", "\[Rule]", "{", 
    StyleBox["r", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SqrtBox[
     RowBox[{"1", "-", 
      SuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["r", "TI"], "2"]}]], 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", "\[CurlyPhi]"}]], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7601e5fe-da14-4c93-8b9d-e159ff9fddba"],
 ". Therefore, a pure qubit state is fully characterized by only two real \
parameters."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d94746c6-7bbb-4323-abed-14d04b7f22b7"],

Cell["Bra\[Dash]Ket Notation and Inner Products", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"7557dd88-7d95-4b04-9bde-7365a6de338b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the quantum mechanics literature, a state vector is usually denoted by a \
ket. For example, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bc88f9b2-768c-4db2-a4c1-516bed73f318"],
 " can represent a generic pure state such as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "038288dd-b977-4bec-b16a-0f9765438f3f"],
 ". The Hermitian conjugate (complex conjugate transpose) of a ket is denoted \
by a bra. For the state above, the corresponding bra is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Bra"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"-", 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b2ffc379-4667-4afe-a404-c93a1ec0cd37"],
 ". The inner product of two states ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "1"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "45576d2b-2f24-4b3a-b4d2-56111626d6e0"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "2"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "60ff97bc-b129-40fb-9bcf-493020010d94"],
 " is written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "1"], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "2"]},
   "BraKet"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e0eeccad-4bcf-4f08-a3b8-e54a6dfa33c8"],
 ", which means the dot product of the bra ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "1"]},
   "Bra"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e67fc0ae-e6be-4e80-9823-987e6fbdb86d"],
 " with the ket |\[Psi]\:2082\:27e9."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e6606556-7b65-4db6-907c-53bafeadb323"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Define ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "1"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5a777920-0e72-4889-a7c9-d0ffba2e1760"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], "2"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "52c29da6-afe8-4dda-89ee-00b8a4b26715"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4d124244-7c8e-463a-8a78-bed47578d7ac"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"\[Psi]1", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"\[Theta]1", "/", "2"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"E", "^", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[Phi]1"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
      RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[Theta]1", "/", "2"}], "]"}]}]}], "}"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"\[Psi]2", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
      RowBox[{"\[Theta]2", "/", "2"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"E", "^", 
       RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[Phi]2"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
      RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[Theta]2", "/", "2"}], "]"}]}]}], "}"}]}], ";"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[13]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"19660d2a-5782-47e6-989c-345ef893737b"],

Cell["Calculate their inner product:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3166bec7-a03f-4943-9b22-fd3eccf46684"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "\[Psi]1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]2"}], ",",
    " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
     "\[Theta]1", " ", "|", " ", "\[Theta]2", " ", "|", " ", "\[Phi]1", " ", "|",
       " ", 
      RowBox[{"\\\n", "\[Phi]2"}]}], ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", " ", 
    "Reals"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[14]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"5e79fd63-9a2e-473d-af91-010416cd11bd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that Mathematica does not force the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]row vs. \
column\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] distinction for rank-1 lists (what we usually \
call vectors) in the same way introductory linear algebra does. A vector is \
represented as a single list, rather than explicitly as a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "\[Times]", 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2d1037eb-d620-454e-ac06-188e385f8d6a"],
 " row matrix or an ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[Times]", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "446deb82-1a4a-4c6e-b97b-79becb0bdc9d"],
 " column matrix. As a result, ",
 ButtonBox["Transpose",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Transpose.html"], None}],
 " has no visible effect on a vector (a 1D list), while it does change a \
matrix (a 2D list) by swapping rows and columns."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"767ef2ca-fb2e-4b9a-9a5d-b27b80c46cc1"],

Cell["\<\
Visualize the transposition on a vector as described in linear algebra:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e1d5761a-0ecd-4369-b74a-f70665b8be5c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "1", "]"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "2", "]"}]}], "}"}], 
      "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Row", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"ArrayPlot", "[", 
       RowBox[{"m", ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Tiny"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Mesh", " ", "->", " ", "All"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"MeshStyle", " ", "->", " ", "Black"}]}], "]"}], ",", "\n", 
      "    ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*OverscriptBox[\\(\[LongRightArrow]\\), \
\\(Transpose\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
      RowBox[{"ArrayPlot", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Transpose", "@", "m"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Tiny"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Mesh", " ", "->", " ", "All"}], ",", " ", "\n", "    ", 
        RowBox[{"MeshStyle", " ", "->", " ", "Black"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], 
    "]"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[15]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"86200b8c-435d-45de-82bd-2a70edddbd1d"],

Cell["Visualize the transposition on a matrix:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6cd0d57f-f9f3-4499-bf5b-b88ba271b5f4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "1", "]"}], ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "2", "]"}]}], "}"}], ",",
        " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "3", "]"}], ",", " ", 
         "\n", "     ", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "4", "]"}]}], "}"}]}], 
      "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Row", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"ArrayPlot", "[", 
       RowBox[{"m", ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Tiny"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Mesh", " ", "->", " ", "All"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"MeshStyle", " ", "->", " ", "Black"}]}], "]"}], ",", "\n", 
      "    ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*OverscriptBox[\\(\[LongRightArrow]\\), \
\\(Transpose\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
      RowBox[{"ArrayPlot", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Transpose", "@", "m"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Tiny"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Mesh", " ", "->", " ", "All"}], ",", " ", "\n", "    ", 
        RowBox[{"MeshStyle", " ", "->", " ", "Black"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], 
    "]"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[16]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"1f73a689-5d06-4a8d-9102-8aa9b5034391"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If one is very serious about keeping the convention of linear algebra for \
vectors (as a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "\[Times]", 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0dc80067-c4ef-445e-a222-67b90602c634"],
 " row matrix or an ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[Times]", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cd09b9be-f914-43e3-b6f2-53bb891e0959"],
 " column matrix), then one should consider a construct as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9692d816-d325-4965-ad4a-30b5d0425abf"],
 ". However, I will adopt the usual Mathematica\[CloseCurlyQuote]s convention \
with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b90aab2a-0f7f-4db0-a385-cc895c4f1414"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3167e795-ffae-44c2-9628-b328bc89d1af"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If one is very serious about preserving the usual linear-algebra \
convention, treating vectors explicitly as either a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "\[Times]", 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "935774a4-afd0-4e3f-ad7d-ffe084f65907"],
 " row matrix or an ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[Times]", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "192b5d73-b758-46a0-aa1e-9e8f3d2508b8"],
 " column matrix, then it can be helpful to represent a \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]row vector\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] as a nested list. \
For example, one may define ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fb020faa-6bc4-4dc2-aa1d-c707e30165a9"],
 " which is a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"1", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0e7eb2d9-d301-4d7e-913e-bbbf45e08e13"],
 " matrix in Mathematica. In that representation, operations like Transpose \
behave exactly as in linear algebra, converting ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3f92d81e-f347-4b81-84a3-9d6b5df7c749"],
 " into the corresponding ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "da7480b3-9a7f-48ca-b9c8-c1daacd9b885"],
 " matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], 
     StyleBox["T", "TI"]], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"], "}"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a01458cc-37c2-42a8-a653-82cc9a437e2e"],
 ". However, in what follows I will adopt Mathematica\[CloseCurlyQuote]s \
usual convention and represent a vector simply as a one-dimensional list, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "464151ee-2967-46d2-abcc-0a097f143130"],
 ", keeping in mind that this suppresses the row/column distinction unless we \
deliberately reintroduce it."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7989c039-e0d5-424d-9d60-aad0ea038241"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that transposition does not change ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9f9ea27c-10ee-4615-930e-d98cb9aefefe"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ad94209f-a23e-4d3b-9381-3a37bea462c3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Array", "[", 
      RowBox[{"\[FormalV]", ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Transpose", "[", "vec", "]"}], " ", "==", " ", "vec"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[17]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"2751409e-ff2f-4a56-9e8f-3ab22b77b79f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that transposition changes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], "}", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6c61e973-3e84-4af1-bc52-a46528f12500"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dd9622af-b019-47dd-a9e2-2acefab98a9f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Array", "[", 
      RowBox[{"\[FormalV]", ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Transpose", "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", "vec", "}"}], "]"}], " ", "===", " ", "vec"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[18]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"fef5a288-bf5c-4544-a9df-6df1cee84952"],

Cell["Computational Basis and Superposition", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"ed49a087-f4a0-4239-99b1-14573ba89353"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "32968e85-253c-4c88-aa86-6e19dcd348b0"],
 " can be also written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], " ", "{", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"0", "}", "+", 
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], " ", "{", "0"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c0c9f9e8-1137-41cb-8e65-7f476b4e0f6a"],
 ". The purpose of this representation is to express the state in a specific \
basis. In a two-dimensional Hilbert space, the unit vectors ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"0", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c9e4fcd9-448e-43c4-8eef-6ed771f24fc8"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "0"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1c03d1f1-a17b-4cfd-9f15-da22a5b1b727"],
 " form an orthonormal basis, which means any state vector can be written as \
a linear combination of them. By convention, we usually define ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{"0"},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "1", ",", "0", "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ccf9713a-1c86-4357-a9cb-d815e971f83b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{"1"},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "0", ",", "1", "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a7a50d32-accf-4fba-9843-24f3ec41f006"],
 ". So a general qubit state can be written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"0"},
      "Ket"]}], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7b3af4c2-986d-4b2f-aaee-26c9973c6f5d"],
 ". Note that in some literature the opposite convention is also used, with \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{"1"},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "1", ",", "0", "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "103e402d-afc5-482f-8acd-1a04a53d0a31"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{"0"},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "0", ",", "1", "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "84d0e795-cabd-4786-8001-7c6a27218d77"],
 ". In the context of quantum computing, the standard orthonormal basis whose \
elements are unit vectors is called the computational basis. The basis isn\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]t just bookkeeping: it corresponds to a measurement choice. \
Writing the state in a basis is how amplitudes become experimental \
probabilities."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e4517ae4-e5c1-4838-acb4-05d88a2579b4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "One can verify that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", "1"}], ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5821cf5b-a8ae-43f3-84e2-435473e0223e"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", "0"}], ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5e1cc9fb-b497-40b1-82ca-b346e38004e8"],
 " form an orthonormal set by checking their inner products: each vector has \
norm 1, and their inner product with each other is 0. Equivalently, if we \
place the computational basis as the columns (or rows) of a matrix, the \
resulting matrix is the identity matrix, which reflects the fact that they \
form an orthonormal basis."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"53dcb7f6-d554-4c68-a7f1-763cd1e1a4d5"],

Cell["\<\
Verify that stacking the computational basis vectors as the rows of a matrix \
yields the identity matrix:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"209900e4-ef55-41dd-8522-f3d1b460e65f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[19]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"5df12004-de63-4f8c-a6cb-46a8cf01446c"],

Cell["The Bloch Vector Map: Turning a Qubit into Geometry", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"f9352f3a-a118-471f-a52f-4422e97d6f83"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s focus on a generic qubit state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d8b28252-40ce-4d83-9c45-135402d0893f"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "\[Element]", "\:2102"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7536bbda-9f8d-4805-935a-83cb60219121"],
 ", assumed to be normalized ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     TemplateBox[{
       RowBox[{
         StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
      "Abs"], "2"], "+", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     TemplateBox[{
       RowBox[{
         StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
      "Abs"], "2"]}], "=", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "aa2079d8-fff4-4531-9549-9f1f81f3a61d"],
 ". Define a three-component real vector as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", "2", 
     StyleBox["R", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["[",
      SpanMaxSize->1], 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "*"], " ", 
      StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"]}], 
     StyleBox["]",
      SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"2", 
     StyleBox["I", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["m", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["[",
      SpanMaxSize->1], 
     RowBox[{
      SuperscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "*"], " ", 
      StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"]}], 
     StyleBox["]",
      SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     SuperscriptBox[
      TemplateBox[{
        RowBox[{
          StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
       "Abs"], "2"], "-", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      TemplateBox[{
        RowBox[{
          StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "\[VeryThinSpace]"}]},
       "Abs"], "2"]}]}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1e1dd146-8df7-464b-8598-44f353d2f812"],
 ". This vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "20d040a5-ad63-4b5d-a020-0c680daa7cf5"],
 " is called the Bloch vector associated with the state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", " ", 
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"]}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6d844968-b489-4926-98af-64808928ecf6"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"909803c3-7333-4e2b-8e46-eefe505426a6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Define a function that takes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Beta]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7ca8c1d9-460b-42f1-a2eb-a9336ba5afe9"],
 " and returns the Bloch vector:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c2bbe267-497f-4359-b32a-9d48f4c6bb2e"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{"ClearAll", "[", "BlochVector", "]"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"BlochVector", "[", 
   RowBox[{"stateVector_", "?", "VectorQ"}], "]"}], " ", ":=", " ", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Module", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}], " ", "=", " ", "\n", 
      "   ", "stateVector"}], ";", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"2", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Re", "[", 
         RowBox[{"\[Beta]", " ", 
          RowBox[{"Conjugate", "@", "\[Alpha]"}]}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", 
       "   ", 
       RowBox[{"2", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Im", "[", 
         RowBox[{"\[Beta]", " ", 
          RowBox[{"Conjugate", "@", "\[Alpha]"}]}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "\[Alpha]", "]"}], "^", "2"}], " ", "-", " ", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "\[Beta]", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}]}], "}"}]}]}], 
   "]"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[20]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"4fac7f1b-8acc-4116-b36c-41158ed9e413"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This definition isn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t arbitrary: for a normalized pure \
state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "15484c03-a1a8-45d8-a043-8ee1d8a4eaf2"],
 ", the three component of Bloch vector are exactly the expectation-value of \
Pauli operators ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Bra"], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d9a1faa3-62b5-4c3b-af7e-2f3b0da8d5e2"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["j", "TI"], "=", 
    StyleBox["x", "TI"]}], ",", 
   StyleBox["y", "TI"], ",", 
   StyleBox["z", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d3582e43-141c-40e1-afab-80c12b09cde1"],
 ". That\[CloseCurlyQuote]s why the Bloch vector is operational: it\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]s what you can measure."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f74daeb9-3ef2-406d-8b83-5b9ff5513b33"],

Cell["\<\
Verify that the norm of the Bloch vector is equal to the squared norm of the \
state vector:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"79eea71f-b303-48ee-9904-64d955a82b9f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"With", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"stateVector", " ", "=", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"\[Alpha]", ",", " ", "\[Beta]"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
    "\n", "  ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
      RowBox[{"BlochVector", "[", "stateVector", "]"}], "]"}], " ", "==", " ",
      "\n", "   ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Norm", "[", "stateVector", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}]}], "]"}], " ", "//",
   " ", "FullSimplify"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[21]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"04d0e746-2573-4d4a-82fe-878763ea602c"],

Cell["\<\
Therefore, the norm of the Bloch vector for a normalized pure state is always \
1. This means that, as we consider all possible normalized pure qubit states, \
their Bloch vectors lie on the unit sphere in three dimensions. This unit \
sphere is called the Bloch sphere (or the Poincar\[EAcute] sphere in the \
context of optics).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"30a20d4e-9f1a-465d-be98-0b956c8a40c8"],

Cell["Visualize the Bloch sphere:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8ba64679-5e7b-45df-bc12-bb5395bbf74d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[22]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"831b08f7-2cd8-4e3e-8ab8-46e781262d28"],

Cell["\<\
As you can see, the axes are labeled in a particular way. These labels \
correspond to kets that represent eigenstates of the Pauli matrices. We shall \
discuss them in more detail later.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4b807bef-9c2e-4133-bf58-8fc1c06ae56b"],

Cell["\<\
There are, of course, different conventions for denoting these kets. For \
example, in optics it is common to use different labels for the same states, \
such as those corresponding to horizontal/vertical, diagonal/antidiagonal, or \
right/left circular photon polarization.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4f841c33-6d4f-4c2f-8970-2b5c4a1a8551"],

Cell["Visualize the Bloch sphere using labels from Optics:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f03c25ba-197f-4093-92f3-8feb7649fb51"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"\"\<Labels\>\"", " ", "->", " ", "\"\<Optics\>\""}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[23]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"b069208c-2fb3-4684-aace-58a6bd795b7f"],

Cell["The Bloch Vector: Cartesian and Spherical Coordinates", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"c92ea339-e259-41e1-8073-3e9030d04720"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Recall that a pure qubit state, in its most general form, can be written as \
",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f0ec499c-05f8-43e2-9439-e3daa2a72556"],
 ". A key result is that the angles \[Theta] and \[Phi] are exactly the usual \
spherical coordinates on the Bloch sphere. In what follows, we will show this \
explicitly by direct computation."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"603d0844-f8fe-49e6-9106-23687fa36d11"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate the Bloch vector for the state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "278cc00d-3278-479a-b2db-3f60bab24d84"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"81f75468-1b7d-4660-9e3e-004d6e87d7aa"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"BlochVector", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Cos", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[Theta]", "/", "2"}], "]"}], ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "^", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
       RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
        RowBox[{"\[Theta]", "/", "2"}], "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Theta]", " ", "|", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", 
    " ", "\n", "  ", "Reals"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[24]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"4788da02-7859-4e01-b9ae-7d729b600c07"],

Cell["\<\
As one can see, angles \[Theta] and \[Phi] are exactly the standard spherical \
coordinates on the unit sphere.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6cc5a6ef-48ee-4157-af9f-b2b308937e3a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Transform a point on the unit sphere from spherical coordinates, specified \
by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1"}], ",", 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b3ebb96d-881d-49d8-aa5e-9efb712782a3"],
 ", into Cartesian coordinates:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b328e027-6ce5-49c8-a5d8-a0022b13d276"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"CoordinateTransform", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"\"\<Spherical\>\"", " ", "->", " ", "\"\<Cartesian\>\""}], ",", 
   " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "\[Theta]", ",", " ", "\[Phi]"}], "}"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[25]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"2af4c803-545f-4f32-b2d9-42e8d90a1854"],

Cell["\<\
Now the motivation for having \[Theta]/2 in the state vector is clear: if we \
used \[Theta] instead of \[Theta]/2, the components of the Bloch vector would \
involve 2\[Theta], and we would obtain an extra factor of 2 in the spherical \
angles on the Bloch sphere.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ed60d84f-fd34-44fa-9308-1ddfa22221e0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Calculate the Bloch vector for the state",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "956d2904-56f4-4459-8b15-b36b443dc0f3"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a7e91371-3a59-4c75-9d8f-bc3e0fe16cd3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"BlochVector", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}], ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"E", "^", 
        RowBox[{"(", 
         RowBox[{"I", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}]}], " ", 
       RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}]}]}], "}"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"\[Theta]", " ", "|", " ", "\[Phi]"}], ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", 
    " ", "Reals"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[26]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"9820aa04-b6b4-4393-9e9f-5439a5b27a0d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "That said, the main motivation for ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b7e19685-aad2-480b-9848-a4837a4e7c25"],
 " choice rather ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cf334e2e-f974-48cb-98e2-c1032698014a"],
 " comes from the fact that ",
 ButtonBox["SU(2)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SpecialUnitaryGroup.html"], None}],
 " acts on the Bloch vector as an ",
 ButtonBox["SO(3)",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://mathworld.wolfram.com/SpecialOrthogonalGroup.html"], None}],
 " rotation. It means if you rotate the qubit state by a unitary (a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d855b1db-184b-4c1f-997a-69171e50a700"],
 " SU(2) matrix), then the corresponding Bloch arrow rotates in ordinary 3D \
space by a rotation matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData["\[ScriptCapitalR]"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "85e410bd-c0d5-4d5e-965c-371dcea23af1"],
 " (a ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"3", "\[Times]", "3"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "be984b06-8629-49f1-ac16-48c5250f1079"],
 " SO(3) matrix): from \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]spinor dance\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] to \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]arrow dance\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]. We shall discuss this later."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c86028a9-cb6b-4a9b-98fb-96739e27660e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "So this is a very interesting analogy. The quantum state vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
      StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4618d0f5-9e72-4002-b9a5-9ba5b7543084"],
 " is mapped into a vector in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\:211d", "3"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "100ad8b2-5c9c-47e6-a665-b49822a427d0"],
 " that is fully parametrized by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["r", "TI"]}], ",", 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7335e2c3-5033-4404-b85a-ccad220f4606"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["r", "TI"], "=", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "35fe959d-0e5a-4ead-bd4a-826de42cf8ab"],
 " for pure states. Later on, we will introduce another class of quantum \
states called mixed states that correspond to points inside of the Bloch \
sphere (meaning ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["r", "TI"], "<", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "02abc4ba-dd4e-4823-84e0-9d0024ddaab6"],
 ")."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4224565a-4f5d-49dd-a30c-c2d6ddfa2ee5"],

Cell["\<\
Pauli Matrices Appear: Axes, Eigenstates, and Bloch-Sphere Landmarks\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6c8b5d19-355f-468b-b19c-fb75a0d13332"],

Cell["Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s look at the Bloch sphere again.", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c0ee7fb5-97a8-4c81-9167-5d2eb5c2e5b6"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[27]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"5e36a528-3171-4046-ac04-f7086eb14e93"],

Cell["\<\
As mentioned, the axis labels correspond to kets that represent eigenstates \
of the Pauli matrices.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4693d285-2e97-4fa8-bf7c-63fb5670ed1d"],

Cell["\<\
Show matrix form of Pauli operators (matrices) together with the identity \
operator:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2d2f9b73-fa1d-4ea0-8bfe-832532a4612b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\[DoubleStruckCapitalI]\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(x\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", 
     " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(y\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", 
     " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(z\\)]\\)\>\""}], 
    "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"MatrixForm", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "j", "]"}], ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"j", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[28]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"14806dfc-2fa0-497e-a6a6-7d7e163d7d22"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Another common notation for Pauli matrices is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "1"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "aa970cd4-532c-4d6a-8a62-39000964fdf1"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f35806fe-7ec6-4871-b7a1-8375be637ed1"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "3"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "22ea7102-7279-467b-a44b-2e634c9677c8"],
 ". Note that the identity matrix can be denoted by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "0"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2e40f8b6-79ec-4650-9f84-388fdfacf64c"],
 ". Of course, the more common notation for the identity operator is ",
 Cell[BoxData["\|01d540"], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2c326a8e-cbab-4f93-9b14-1ed7252148f0"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"486f9762-9dc6-4b30-9e17-f1148ba52dc1"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(0\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", 
     " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(1\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", 
     " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(2\\)]\\)\>\"", ",", 
     " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*SubscriptBox[\\(\[Sigma]\\), \\(3\\)]\\)\>\""}], 
    "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"MatrixForm", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "j", "]"}], ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"j", ",", " ", "0", ",", " ", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[29]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"c2ef21a7-9050-4dcf-9c40-2e3065906be0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let us now focus more closely on the concept of eigenstates. An eigenstate \
of an operator is a state such that, when the operator acts on it, the result \
is the same state multiplied by a constant, called the eigenvalue. \
Mathematically, this is written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["a", "TI"]]},
     "Ket"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["a", "TI"]]},
     "Ket"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "73b3ac0e-2a78-44fc-bb96-2e1402021e29"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["A", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fd692ede-9334-49ca-a241-c9f5a162557c"],
 " is the operator/matrix, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["a", "TI"]]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "29b936bd-0956-48eb-95a7-268526304505"],
 " is the eigenstate, and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["a", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "15857d84-62bf-4637-aeb5-13e86c0b435e"],
 " is the eigenvalue."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8f25e73d-7b03-4558-8ca1-cbd91ecf447e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Show ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"0", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cc88ed39-5c77-43a4-b31c-e50a7c988564"],
 " is the eigenstate of Pauli-Z with the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fdea795e-9c62-4674-b06a-741a6754008b"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c57d1d6a-3c82-4213-b182-8fa624ddc137"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vec"}], " ", "==",
     " ", "vec"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[30]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"b1707ae8-dfbd-4302-af47-c7c318184b1c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Show ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "0"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "dd06779a-a8db-4252-93ca-e09d46c265e4"],
 " is the eigenstate of Pauli-Z with the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "8584a73e-b158-480a-a56d-b633cb8bd2c7"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3947c962-3342-467d-819b-0e6d02633e3d"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vec"}], " ", "==",
     " ", 
    RowBox[{"-", "vec"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[31]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"14a798e2-02aa-4f6b-96b9-5cff6434bbdc"],

Cell["Calculate the eigenvalues of Pauli-X:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a6299d22-1c90-4222-bd64-7ec3ba994da5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Eigenvalues", "[", 
  RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[32]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"38bf73a8-d164-4182-9639-5d09ef2b5ca8"],

Cell["Calculate the eigenstates of Pauli-X:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"414ddbd7-47d6-46c7-8610-3a9a33fca573"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
  RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[33]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"1e8919d0-c29d-49ce-aab2-ba3c65ff0408"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Show ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", "-", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5fb10b23-1701-47d5-a6b9-235aaaa13e2b"],
 " is the eigenstate of Pauli-X with the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "16cea109-c1e2-4600-8e61-1c2bae12845f"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"35544989-e641-48a5-a4d9-265a4641a722"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vec"}], " ", "==",
     " ", 
    RowBox[{"-", "vec"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[34]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"953095bf-6d7f-4d10-86e7-6847b1327b85"],

Cell["\<\
If we multiply an eigenstate by a nonzero constant, it is still an eigenstate \
of the same operator with the same eigenvalue.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2ec294fe-b67e-40c7-b14a-06c7bb09d625"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Show that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"1", "/", 
    SqrtBox["2"], "{", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"-", "1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2785588c-ba8c-4dcc-89c6-36e91ce7fc40"],
 " is eigenstate of Pauli-X with the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "176d3bba-b039-48e7-bf15-2848493c959b"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d94e18d1-3cc9-4575-b8e0-fb35d6b28093"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"1", "/", 
       RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}], " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vec"}], " ", "==",
     " ", 
    RowBox[{"-", "vec"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[35]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"acdea457-4183-4306-90c6-6991ff8ae687"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Show that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"1", "/", 
    SqrtBox["2"], "{", "1"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"1", "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2a368fe8-7da7-4c27-b684-bdc172810f6c"],
 " is eigenstate of Pauli-X with the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"+", "1"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "607c4610-2a0d-4dbc-b5f0-26f2568db027"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0bc712f2-81ef-4f89-9fd7-2d6bce3b7854"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"vec", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"1", "/", 
       RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}], " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "vec"}], " ", "==",
     " ", "vec"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[36]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"48a892d5-c7ce-432c-8927-c787d4c25c02"],

Cell["\<\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s plot normalized eigenstates of Pauli-X operator in the \
Bloch sphere.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ae1f696b-8161-467a-8da6-f87594d4fba2"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normalize", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[37]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"d511e357-962d-42a4-9720-408ac549e62b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As one can see, the eigenstates of Pauli-X lie along the x-axis of the \
Bloch sphere, with the +1 eigenstate pointing in the positive x direction and \
the \[Minus]1 eigenstate in the negative x direction. Note they are usually \
denoted as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[PlusMinus]"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "1", ",", "\[PlusMinus]", "1", "}", "/", 
   SqrtBox["2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "51b58966-5843-4dac-b00a-a76d9e939cfc"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"732876f7-abb0-4451-9127-c6cc568f052f"],

Cell["\<\
Calculate Bloch vectors corresponding to eigenstates of Pauli-X:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fad26917-34dc-4265-9cec-844968baa571"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"x\\\", \
\\\"+\\\"]},\\\n\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"x\\\", \\\"-\\\"]},\
\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"BlochVector", "@*", "Normalize"}], " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[38]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"50f26458-df65-4729-a507-77303589bae7"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In a similar manner, eigenstates of Pauli-Y lie along y-axis. They are \
usually denoted as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["y", "TI"], "\[PlusMinus]"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", "1", ",", "\[PlusMinus]", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], "}", "/", 
   SqrtBox["2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e6c2d060-979e-4da6-9717-faee36a2b9e8"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f9108c0b-df67-4f91-b152-9fd42da0d83a"],

Cell["Compute Bloch vector for eigenstates of Pauli-Y:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ebd2b57d-9fa3-40f0-b5e6-028da399eae0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"y\\\", \
\\\"+\\\"]},\\\n\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"y\\\", \\\"-\\\"]},\
\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"BlochVector", "@*", "Normalize"}], " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}], "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[39]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"2370e0fd-d698-49db-b154-3a6d92a37b6d"],

Cell["Plot eigenstates of Pauli-Y in the Bloch sphere:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e8a5c7aa-6f81-46d1-a89e-4dec23dff1d7"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normalize", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[40]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"b0c9a865-aef1-4499-aca2-e3b26681d589"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The eigenstates of Pauli-Y are also denoted by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["R", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["y", "TI"], "+"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0a5c1d28-72a1-4bfd-aab2-c7f8ad28291c"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["L", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["y", "TI"], "-"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "64c400f5-a0c8-48cb-95c8-3ad0a12b2686"],
 ", following a standard convention in optics and photon polarization."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"53af0f7a-8ce1-4755-8ccb-d5f47a61f37f"],

Cell["\<\
Plot eigenstates of Pauli-Y in the Bloch sphere using optics labels:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ef756b99-0ca9-4a98-a52a-144f2bc41eeb"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normalize", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"\"\<Labels\>\"", " ", "->", " ", "\"\<Optics\>\""}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[41]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"2c0bb7e3-114a-47f3-a70c-007977950fcb"],

Cell["\<\
The computational basis corresponds to the eigenstates of Pauli-Z and is \
aligned with the z-axis.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"027f6d9e-9808-4640-a544-ea15c5e106ab"],

Cell["Plot eigenstates of Pauli-Z in the Bloch sphere:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fba0a95d-3649-4706-92f7-734f22cf5d07"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Normalize", " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}], "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Small"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[42]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"7451de5f-d8ba-4bef-a92f-0bbd1b0c16be"],

Cell["Compute Bloch vectors for eigenstates of Pauli-Z:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0f5c23f2-5cc3-4d6e-befe-d83ec1b41b9e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"z\\\", \
\\\"+\\\"]},\\\n\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"z\\\", \\\"-\\\"]},\
\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"BlochVector", "@*", "Normalize"}], " ", "/@", " ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "3", "]"}], "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[43]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"4c7728fb-fa3a-43b8-aa75-739b9b4b44c6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The most generic pure qubit state, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", "{", 
   StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], ",", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"]}]], 
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["[",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
   StyleBox["]",
    SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2dde2e7f-f9fd-40b9-9fbb-b24af8751401"],
 ", is given by the Bloch vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], " ", 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], " ", 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6b6afc01-f700-4789-99ef-18355d8ab27f"],
 " with \[Theta] and \[Phi] spherical-coordinate angles. \
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s visualize it."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"27d19145-413a-477f-a831-dc6618975807"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Manipulate", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"ResourceFunction", "[", "\"\<BlochSpherePlot\>\"", "]"}], "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "\[Phi]", "]"}], " ", 
        RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", "   ", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}], " ", 
        RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "\[Phi]", "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "270"}], ",", " ", "\n", "  ", 
     RowBox[{"\"\<NumberOfGreatCircles\>\"", " ", "->", " ", "4"}], ",", " ", 
     "\n", "  ", 
     RowBox[{"\"\<NumberOfSmallCircles\>\"", " ", "->", " ", "3"}]}], "]"}], ",",
    " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"\[Theta]", ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "3"}], ",", " ", "\n", 
       "   ", "\"\<Polar angle \[Theta]\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", "  ", 
     "0", ",", " ", "\[Pi]"}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"\[Phi]", ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"\[Pi]", "/", "4"}], ",", 
       " ", "\"\<Azimuthal angle \[Phi]\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "0", ",", 
     " ", 
     RowBox[{"2", " ", "\[Pi]"}]}], "}"}], ",", "\n", "  ", 
   RowBox[{"Item", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<State vector \
\\!\\(\\*FormBox[\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\\"\[Psi]\\\"},\n\\\"Ket\\\"] = {Cos[\
\[Theta]/2], \\*SuperscriptBox[\\(\[ExponentialE]\\), \\(\[ImaginaryI]\\\\ \
\[Phi]\\)] Sin[\[Theta]/2]}\\),\nTraditionalForm]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Alignment", " ", "->", " ", "Center"}]}], "]"}], ",", " ", "\n",
    " ", 
   RowBox[{"Item", "[", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<Bloch vector \\!\\(\\*FormBox[\\({Cos[\[Phi]]\\\\ Sin[\
\[Theta]], Sin[\[Theta]]\\\\ Sin[\[Phi]], Cos[\[Theta]]}\\),\n\
TraditionalForm]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Alignment", " ", "->", " ", "Center"}]}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"SaveDefinitions", " ", ":>", " ", "True"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[44]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"1e71838a-23f6-44c5-a47d-f070dbdfd627"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The Pauli matrices are among the most important observables for \
single-qubit systems. A quantum observable is a physical quantity (like \
energy, position, spin) represented by a linear operator that is Hermitian. A \
linear operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["A", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5770251b-cdd7-4ed3-8df8-692901b31353"],
 " on a finite-dimensional Hilbert space is Hermitian if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["A", "TI"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "dbf8baa1-811b-45cc-9755-166b8f3c0559"],
 " where \[Dagger] means the conjugate transpose."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7accf931-63cd-4c36-86d4-e8759d9bfe91"],

Cell["\<\
The conjugate transpose (also called the Hermitian conjugate in quantum \
mechanics) of a matrix is obtained by taking the transpose (switching rows \
and columns) and then taking the complex conjugate of each entry. The order \
of these two operations does not matter: you can transpose first and then \
conjugate, or conjugate first and then transpose.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f23ff0fb-9b53-4ceb-8753-846eb0f628fa"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"ClearAll", "[", "A", "]"}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"With", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"a", " ", "=", " ", 
      RowBox[{"Array", "[", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
          RowBox[{"A", ",", " ", "##"}], "]"}], " ", "&"}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{"2", ",", " ", "2"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
    "\n", "  ", 
    RowBox[{"Row", "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
      "a", ",", 
       " ", "\"\< \\!\\(\\*OverscriptBox[\\(\[LongRightArrow]\\), \\(\\\\ \
\\(Conjugate\\(\\\\ \\)\\(transpose\\)\\(\\\\ \\)\\)\\)]\\) \>\"", ",", " ", 
       "\n", "    ", 
       RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "a", "]"}]}], "}"}], "]"}]}], "]"}],
   " ", "//", " ", "TraditionalForm"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[45]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"e8d7ecea-8816-4138-8c74-abebab2d1055"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Impose the Hermiticity condition on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "03bad19a-b3c9-4f87-8ffd-ff4d8febcdb0"],
 " matrix:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8e7caebd-7cc7-4ad8-96b2-11ddc33c9341"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"a", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Array", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
         RowBox[{"A", ",", " ", "##"}], "]"}], " ", "&"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"2", ",", " ", "2"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n",
    " ", 
   RowBox[{"Reduce", "[", 
    RowBox[{"a", " ", "==", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "a", "]"}]}], "]"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",\

 CellLabel->
  "In[46]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"500a22f4-ebba-427a-923d-4e067d590514"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As one can see, the diagonal elements of a Hermitian matrix must be real, \
and the off-diagonal elements must be complex conjugates of each other. This \
means any ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "30027658-e9bd-46a6-ab78-0f95bdb5ed8f"],
 " Hermitian matrix can be written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
     {
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "1"], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "2"], "+", 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "3"]}]},
     {
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "2"], "-", 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "3"]}], 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "4"]}
    }], ")"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "10b279c7-4355-4bcd-ab1a-884f80a07057"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3", ",", "4"}]], "\[Element]", "\:211d"}]], 
  "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "acfbc065-b67c-43da-9290-bd0049c0f97c"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0072a17f-c660-4797-8b6c-9ecc3e9b7946"],

Cell["\<\
For a 2x2 matrix, visualize diagonal and off-diagonal elements:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b0b98efe-9378-4522-b128-66c74c0a75c4"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Legended", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"MatrixPlot", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ImageSize", " ", "->", " ", "Tiny"}], ",", " ", "\n", "  ", 
     RowBox[{"ColorRules", " ", "->", " ", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"1", " ", "->", " ", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "1", "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
        
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"-", "1"}], " ", "->", " ", 
         RowBox[{
          RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], 
       "}"}]}]}], "]"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{"SwatchLegend", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "1", "]"}], ",", " ", 
       "\n", "   ", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"ColorData", "[", "97", "]"}], "[", "2", "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", 
     " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"\"\<Diagonal elements\>\"", ",", 
       " ", "\"\<Off-diagonal elements\>\""}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[47]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"15cd51ef-7359-4341-a8b0-f328d127fbce"],

Cell["Verify that Pauli operators are Hermitian:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0b3fdff5-a6f3-47b7-8f33-4d27cc7aac6b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"HermitianMatrixQ", "[", 
    RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "j", "]"}], "]"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"j", ",", " ", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[48]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"c2b4d6f7-edf0-4b98-a01e-fb833fe0c5d0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For a Hermitian operator, the eigenvalues are real numbers. This follows \
from the condition ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["A", "TI"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fab91a4b-a3b6-487b-8b11-7877de92d66e"],
 ": if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["a", "TI"]]},
     "Ket"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["a", "TI"]]},
     "Ket"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "39772804-3177-4395-a1ec-4e83ee2a2e5e"],
 ", then one can show that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["a", "TI"], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], "*"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9ac3a4f9-7b85-4d4b-ac72-37c802df9204"],
 " which means the eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["a", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bc91f8b9-2ad1-46ba-81e5-342132f616c0"],
 " must be a real number."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"15de4b21-bb74-4456-81e9-f478d877a9fe"],

Cell["\<\
For a generic 2\[Times]2 Hermitian matrix, verify that eigenvalues are always \
real:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"52c7a594-b30e-43e4-ab29-49d8d862abde"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Eigenvalues", "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"a1", ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{"a2", " ", "+", " ", 
          RowBox[{"I", " ", "a3"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"a2", " ", "-", " ", 
          RowBox[{"I", " ", "a3"}]}], ",", " ", "a4"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], "]"}],
     " ", "\[Element]", " ", "\n", "  ", "Reals"}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
     "a1", " ", "|", " ", "a2", " ", "|", " ", "a3", " ", "|", " ", "a4"}], 
     ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", " ", "Reals"}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[49]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"03770811-a771-4590-bd69-fad21866319f"],

Cell["\<\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s also verify these features numerically by generating a \
random 2\[Times]2 Hermitian matrix and checking that its diagonal entries are \
real, its off-diagonal entries are complex conjugates of each other, and its \
eigenvalues are real.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"918a1139-16cf-4061-bfa3-b28d2e27ac59"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Generate a random ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "80f6b052-e0d9-4a35-9049-e41c066f4647"],
 " Hermitian matrix:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dca3f56d-f641-4408-b0bb-9b959ff6fb91"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"hermitian", " ", "=", " ", "\n", "  ", 
   RowBox[{"With", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"a", " ", "=", " ", "\n", "     ", 
       RowBox[{"RandomComplex", "[", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{
           RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"-", "1"}], " ", "-", " ", "I"}], ",", " ", 
           RowBox[{"1", " ", "+", " ", "I"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{"2", ",", " ", "2"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{"a", " ", "+", " ", "\n", "      ", 
        RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "a", "]"}]}], ")"}], "/", "2"}]}], 
    "]"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"hermitian", " ", "//", " ", "Chop"}], " ", "//", " ", 
  "MatrixForm"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[50]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"121a9330-4405-49af-85d1-56cfea81d206"],

Cell["Verify that this matrix is Hermitian:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b193ad98-706c-4abb-92f1-168fc2e75ae5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"HermitianMatrixQ", "[", "hermitian", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[51]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"241c2c03-8538-413f-b255-8e64dd32ce58"],

Cell["Verify that its diagonal entries are real:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ff2ca4e9-1415-4130-a386-7281271aa202"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
   RowBox[{"Diagonal", "[", "hermitian", "]"}], "]"}], " ", "\[Element]", " ",
   "Reals"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[52]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"93a7b8d3-f588-41bd-a4e4-1887b7c791fb"],

Cell["\<\
Verify that its off-diagonal entries are complex conjugates of each other:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f3c88935-ffc3-4c24-968f-890d1e044aa5"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"hermitian", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
   RowBox[{"hermitian", "[", 
    RowBox[{"[", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", " ", "1"}], "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[53]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"a6627566-7061-4ff4-92b9-c04bdde5e547"],

Cell["Verify that its eigenvalues are real:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"abe55b24-93bc-467d-a8e7-615e2a46d51e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Eigenvalues", "[", "hermitian", "]"}], " ", "\[Element]", " ", 
  "Reals"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[54]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"28294f44-00b4-40f9-9ef9-a978bc262092"],

Cell["\<\
Additionally, for a Hermitian operator, eigenstates corresponding to \
different eigenvalues are orthogonal.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3d628c02-9982-48cc-8c10-376579684601"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that for a generic Hermitian operator as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
     {
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "1"], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "2"], "+", 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "3"]}]},
     {
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "2"], "-", 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], "3"]}], 
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "4"]}
    }], ")"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a597fcee-d304-478e-8f8f-b344375e25a6"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3", ",", "4"}]], "\[Element]", "\:211d"}]], 
  "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "aeaa2e6d-f625-4a77-8771-377ed3aa6a88"],
 ", eigenstates are orthogonal:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2230c1b4-d2e2-4e5e-b828-e64508a83e79"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"FullSimplify", "[", "\n", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "#1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "#2"}], " ", 
     "&"}], " ", "@@", " ", "\n", "  ", 
    RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{"a1", ",", " ", 
         RowBox[{"a2", " ", "+", " ", 
          RowBox[{"I", " ", "a3"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"{", 
        RowBox[{
         RowBox[{"a2", " ", "-", " ", 
          RowBox[{"I", " ", "a3"}]}], ",", " ", "a4"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], 
     "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
     "a1", " ", "|", " ", "a2", " ", "|", " ", "a3", " ", "|", " ", "\n", 
      "    ", "a4"}], ")"}], " ", "\[Element]", " ", "Reals"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[55]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"851597e1-54a9-481f-8599-c25398a7eefa"],

Cell["\<\
Verify that the eigenstates of the numerical Hermitian operator above are \
orthogonal:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d6d85e3f-3d06-4eaf-86a1-9d774df817df"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "#1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "#2"}], " ", "&"}],
    " ", "@@", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Eigenvectors", "[", "hermitian", "]"}]}], " ", "//", " ", 
  "Chop"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[56]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"7393ceb1-6fc9-4399-b724-6c8700a00e42"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note the orthogonality condition can be also written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
    "BraKet"], "\[Proportional]", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f946693c-81d7-4604-8c6d-eab0515d1802"],
 " where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "fdfb4fa8-4ba4-4449-9bbc-7b48ce77de5e"],
 " is the Kronecker delta, which is zero if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["i", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e2146dc2-fd21-437a-8b4c-c5c2bf6ed4d3"],
 " is different from ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c3dfb453-b31c-42cb-b280-a3d813146049"],
 ", and one if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["i", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e2018c86-f85f-4abd-b22c-bcc31b6b2f25"],
 " is the same as: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]], "=", "{", GridBox[{
     {"1", 
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], "=", 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]},
     {"0", 
      RowBox[{
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], "\[NotEqual]", 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]}
    },
    GridBoxAlignment->{"Columns" -> {{Left}}, "Rows" -> {{Baseline}}}]}]], 
  "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ed546f1e-338d-4860-82c9-f14eea23e2e0"],
 " ."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"62d9e611-2380-4e66-8c36-3297b2673ccf"],

Cell["Changing Basis: Unitary Matrices as Basis Machines", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"79bcb5a8-b0e1-48ea-9876-4c9f6631964b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Eigenstates of an observable can be chosen to form an orthonormal basis for \
the corresponding Hilbert space (assuming the observable has a complete set \
of eigenstates; we shall discuss these details). Such a basis is usually \
called as eigenbasis. Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s focus more on the concept of \
basis for the Hilbert space. The computational basis is not the only way to \
define a basis (recall that the computational basis is unit vectors). There \
are infinitely many possible bases for a Hilbert space. For example, any ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0bba2453-519f-41a4-8d5f-23f1368dc553"],
 " unitary matrix defines a new orthonormal basis for a two-dimensional \
Hilbert space when applied to the computational basis vectors. A unitary \
matrix is a matrix such that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["U", "TI"], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"], "=", "\|01d540"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "463d367b-0ddd-4b80-98ae-bc593ba75f4c"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a469c9d0-a161-4fdb-b940-4b64b1e176ba"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Generate a random ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "5fa7e72f-f515-429d-b761-ba58d5fdefbe"],
 " unitary matrix (using ",
 ButtonBox["Haar-measure",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HaarMeasure.html"], None}],
 "):"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"92bab39d-22b6-4820-aa81-773fcdeca752"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"u", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"RandomVariate", "@", 
    RowBox[{"CircularUnitaryMatrixDistribution", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"u", " ", "//", " ", "MatrixForm"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[57]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"83ecc378-a468-41b7-b05f-fc9a1b4d1931"],

Cell["Verify that it is unitary:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"d131301c-6682-4229-adfd-152cd3f45d02"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
   RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
    RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "u", "]"}]}], "]"}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[58]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"9ac7ffe7-5d7d-4c60-a021-891caba83fa4"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The reason we use ",
 ButtonBox["Chop",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Chop.html"], None}],
 " in the code above is that the computation may involve small numerical \
errors due to machine precision. ",
 ButtonBox["Chop",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/Chop.html"], None}],
 " sets these tiny residual values to zero, making the result easier to \
interpret."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"fb6e744f-a50a-4410-af1c-0e1590506bf1"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
  RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "u", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[59]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"52184590-cee5-403f-ac6c-9a28ff90f09c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In a different way, one can say a unitary matrix is a matrix such that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f727c7ec-2369-4c8b-8a8c-69b6c7ab71be"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"47b84905-49e6-43b5-b8ce-9678fd38260a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "For ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["u", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "05fe55d6-87ff-4d7e-b376-9686775ca0c1"],
 " matrix generated above, verify that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "70e650ba-766a-4fab-9864-c87763b69195"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"39e769ed-8697-4ea4-a3c5-bb14f15b8988"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Inverse", "[", "u", "]"}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "u", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[60]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"5f349072-a6df-4bd0-908a-48fd80f82891"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the Wolfram Language, one can directly check if a matrix is unitary or \
not, using ",
 ButtonBox["UnitaryMatrixQ",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/ref/UnitaryMatrixQ.html"], 
    None}],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4b20221d-903b-4dc7-8fea-e6607e26c76e"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"UnitaryMatrixQ", "[", "u", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[61]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"43b5da7f-9505-4079-a946-7dfe7e13ad19"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Now transform the computational basis using the above unitary matrix. This \
produces a new pair of vectors, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"0"},
      "Ket"]}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"]}]}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "9d645963-0623-4567-be66-9536ee884219"],
 ", that define a new basis."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a781cd0d-fb04-4444-bac3-4a8773edf76a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"{", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[62]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"33e6f7b7-6ad2-4aea-bd14-72f3e7f6d069"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Notice that this algebraic computation, applying ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["U", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1eb2c603-27f2-4f50-a393-d6dc90bf27ef"],
 " to the computational basis vectors, is equivalent to reading off the \
columns of the unitary matrix ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["U", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "13080d15-0f88-472e-9f1a-e83ec5718eb5"],
 ". In fact, the first column is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{"0"},
     "Ket"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], ".", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], "}"}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "513532c6-c29d-4752-a015-c56cae92d93a"],
 " and the second column is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{"1"},
     "Ket"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], ".", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "}"}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4675d483-5e52-422d-900d-c61e6f8c49c2"],
 ", both written in the computational basis."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f6a24843-00a1-45cb-b7fe-bb9b1451ffdc"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that new basis vectors are the same as columns of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["u", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cea68d92-f3b4-47e2-a9ee-5070f4e3daff"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"645fac85-8d10-429c-9c52-937d66555eee"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Transpose", "[", "u", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[63]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"7cdaeeee-4d42-4929-93af-03fed4085025"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "If we stack new vectors ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"0"},
      "Ket"]}], ",", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], 
     TemplateBox[{"1"},
      "Ket"]}]}], "}"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "44add98d-3504-47be-8f9b-9a988eb15d45"],
 " as the rows or columns of a matrix, we can then verify that the matrix is \
unitary, which means that the new vectors form an orthonormal set."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"32df6458-d03e-43b2-9525-f8e97233e436"],

Cell["\<\
Stack new vectors as the rows of a matrix, and verify the result is unitary:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3e42b96e-e22a-4eb1-a590-4c100d9cf227"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"{", 
         RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
   "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
     RowBox[{"m", " ", ".", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "m", "]"}]}], "]"}], " ", "==", " ", 
    
    RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[64]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"065350d9-cda6-433d-a940-a1a0e8f1561c"],

Cell["\<\
Stack new vectors as the columns of a matrix, and verify the result is \
unitary:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b55e0d6a-ce09-4a14-a08d-2ad217d6700a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Transpose", "@", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "0"}], "}"}]}], ",", " ", 
        RowBox[{"u", " ", ".", " ", 
         RowBox[{"{", 
          RowBox[{"0", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ",
    "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Chop", "[", 
     RowBox[{"m", " ", ".", " ", 
      RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "m", "]"}]}], "]"}], " ", "==", " ", 
    
    RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[65]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"8d0b0aba-9da0-47fe-963e-cdb7d4843681"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note the orthonormality condition can be also written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
    "BraKet"], "=", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "24073630-a657-4f69-b880-cf7c1c719320"],
 ". In words, the inner product of two basis vectors is 1 when they are the \
same vector and 0 when they are different."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7c450bcd-848d-43ff-ab90-df31b1213050"],

Cell["Coordinates of the Same State in Different Bases", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"52e48e41-4837-456b-a6c4-797ff36dc6bd"],

Cell["\<\
Now let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s discuss how to compute the representation of qubit \
states in a new basis.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f7b00989-cf61-4f11-ae74-ce00384715e5"],

Cell["Define a normal random state vector:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"9ca7c0a0-7485-4a57-9d05-7f7b597194fa"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"\[Psi]", " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Normalize", "[", 
   RowBox[{"RandomComplex", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "1"}], " ", "-", " ", "I"}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"1", " ", "+", " ", "I"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}], 
   "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[66]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"963a50c1-ef6d-4548-b685-4995448df9a5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "3bda06cc-8935-4d8e-95dc-8cffb580dee1"],
 " is normalized:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"45550002-bceb-47be-831a-f36633423774"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"Norm", "[", "\[Psi]", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[67]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"081cf57b-951f-4b5e-9f85-55c5496e3b16"],

Cell["\<\
Compute the normalization factor (which is expected to be 1):\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"36de0b42-27e6-4c72-9f46-169251c8062b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "\[Psi]", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
  "\[Psi]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[68]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"cc30c122-3a97-423b-86e6-129ac499d014"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s define a new orthonormal basis. To do this, we use \
the random ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"2", "\[Times]", "2"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6d1cde9b-9ae1-4d32-a018-94481dd5db8b"],
 " unitary matrix generated before and take its rows as the basis vectors for \
the same two-dimensional Hilbert space."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1f324286-291f-4bb8-91bd-da7832a35058"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"v1", ",", " ", "v2"}], "}"}], " ", "=", " ", "u"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[69]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"c6912431-dce6-4349-98ed-e9fc81aec881"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "When we define the basis vector like above, the unitarity condition can be \
written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["U", "TI"], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"], "}"}], ".", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"], 
    SuperscriptBox["}", "\[Dagger]"], "=", "{", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"]}], ".", 
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1", "*"], ",", 
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2", "*"], "}"}], ",", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"]}], ".", 
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1", "*"], ",", 
   SubscriptBox[
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    SubsuperscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2", "*"], "}", "}"}]}]], 
  "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "20603676-0ba6-4509-8f24-1f21f768cf09"],
 ". Keep in mind that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", "2"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "1cc60bf3-5af6-4ddd-aebe-4d26c1e66ebc"],
 " are vectors. Therefore, the orthonormality condition, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
    "BraKet"], "=", 
   SubsuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], "*"], ".", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "=", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4f3f68a4-d103-4c73-b1ef-ff91589d9d6a"],
 " is the same as unitarity condition of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["u", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4c40c09b-5a28-42d6-9d6e-9c6367905651"],
 " matrix."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2b65c1b6-8b96-499c-9639-1ad2b39081b6"],

Cell["Verify explicitly the orthonormality of new basis elements:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f5e36444-4caf-4c83-a3a5-4e57914803af"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Chop", "@", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"v1", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v1", "]"}]}], ",", " ", 
       RowBox[{"v1", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v2", "]"}]}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"v2", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v1", "]"}]}], ",", " ", "\n", "    ", 
       RowBox[{"v2", " ", ".", " ", 
        RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v2", "]"}]}]}], "}"}]}], "}"}]}], " ", "==",
   " ", 
  RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[70]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"a7668e8e-ba08-4c26-81cd-eba63a2ed29c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The above relation is the same as checking ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   StyleBox["U", "TI"], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"], "=", "\|01d540"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6752ae5d-2394-4607-85be-942ff3be330c"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c1b9d837-c54d-4335-bd81-d7600f49a301"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0ffc90b5-e588-47d4-a846-d6068718663a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In order to express a state vector in the new basis ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", "2"}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "238e0c1c-95d3-4071-a2e3-d30bfdcf66dc"],
 ", we should find the coefficients ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e04c715e-14fd-4d1b-afa4-6590f16bf719"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "73ccdb28-be43-476c-9ce7-5ceee8a44052"],
 " in the linear combination ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
      "Ket"]}], "+", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"]},
      "Ket"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "cb66124b-3d71-454e-966c-7125c3f6f7b9"],
 ". To do this, we use the orthonormality of the basis vectors. If we \
multiply this equation on the left by the bra ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
   "Bra"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d1a3e6bd-a03a-499e-b597-7dd7e3c51d0c"],
 ", only the coefficient of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "92c0628f-57a7-4bb6-ad27-99729cd2a634"],
 " survives: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"], 
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "BraKet"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"], 
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
       "BraKet"]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"], 
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"]},
       "BraKet"]}]}], "=", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f610efb7-5f53-4a8e-9562-e54040119ae6"],
 " because ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["i", "TI"]], 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
    "BraKet"], "=", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Delta]", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], ",", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4f082a8a-6903-418f-84d6-01ef3f743877"],
 ". Similarly, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], 
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "BraKet"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], 
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
       "BraKet"]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"], 
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"]},
       "BraKet"]}]}], "=", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "507b0ff9-72b6-4c86-9763-dde055526313"],
 ". Thus, in general, the expansion coefficients are given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "=", 
   TemplateBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "BraKet"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f7678940-6aea-4a80-9fda-3cd67b744d93"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6890ba6e-c153-4a95-82fa-4b47b1e7b681"],

Cell["Compute the state vector in the new basis:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"b0e82963-0f4b-4878-8faf-36daaf3a482f"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"newStateVector", " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}], ",", 
    " ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "v2", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}]}], 
   "}"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[71]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"3cec972f-7046-4822-adb6-0f08f62c59e3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In a simpler code, the above computation can be done as follows (keep in \
mind ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "1"]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["v", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "2"], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "dafefdb2-399f-4d12-b399-fdbc345ea450"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a4fff99b-0877-48f9-bf94-e765669b7e49"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "u", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[72]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"d14226b1-229c-41df-bd60-c70d21e1f265"],

Cell["\<\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s perform a similar calculation in a different basis. \
This time, consider the normalized eigenstates of the Pauli-X operator.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"542e1e82-1ee9-4aec-9ff5-2d4d8a12320e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Define ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[PlusMinus]"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "430e55bb-6360-4f3d-a97d-78e81bc02388"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"dd20b1f7-c3a2-43e0-b004-0045a77ce654"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"plus", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "1"}], "}"}], "/", 
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"minus", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], "}"}], "/", 
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], ";"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[73]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"6ab88ed2-8d0d-4b74-9ca9-7f7357e10f1b"],

Cell["Verify that these states form an orthonormal set:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"62fd96f0-5f65-4bb7-88b6-4719639d5e5c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"m", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"plus", ",", " ", "minus"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", 
   " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"m", " ", ".", " ", 
     RowBox[{"ConjugateTranspose", "[", "m", "]"}]}], " ", "==", " ", 
    RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[74]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"5df85442-266b-49e8-936b-9faa4d13b522"],

Cell["Compute the state vector in the Pauli-X basis:", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ea02f0ba-8259-4780-b350-8e3fa4bf9acf"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"newStateVectorX", " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"plus", ",", " ", "minus"}], "}"}], "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
   "\[Psi]"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[75]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"e1474168-01a6-4adf-86cb-25796d2641d7"],

Cell["\<\
Note that although the coordinate representation of a state vector is \
different in different bases, the physical state itself is the same. If you \
reconstruct the state by taking the appropriate linear combination in any \
given basis, you obtain the same vector in Hilbert space, as expected.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"851b6253-6f84-4f06-a554-6c7c1934af3b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "1"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "1"]},
       "Ket"]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], "2"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["v", "TI"], "2"]},
       "Ket"]}]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["k", "TI"], "+"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["x", "TI"], "+"]},
       "Ket"]}], "+", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["k", "TI"], "-"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["x", "TI"], "-"]},
       "Ket"]}]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "78529f8a-6555-49ed-b3f1-d77ec87b4439"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"91928440-88b4-4782-ac52-a8acce652b0a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"\[Psi]", " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"newStateVector", " ", ".", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"v1", ",", " ", "v2"}], "}"}]}], " ", "==", " ", 
  RowBox[{"newStateVectorX", " ", ".", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"plus", ",", " ", "minus"}], "}"}]}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[76]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"a8edf3b3-d3c4-426d-afda-d99b6095c4fc"],

Cell["Measurement as Probabilities: Born Rule in the Eigenbasis", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"712b5d59-a714-48cb-9284-fe09f1cd04b5"],

Cell["\<\
What is the main motivation for expressing a state in different bases? \
Besides mathematical advantages that may simplify calculations, an especially \
important reason comes from quantum measurement. Experimental data are \
obtained as probabilities for different measurement outcomes, and these \
probabilities can be read directly from the coefficients in the expansion of \
the state in a chosen basis.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c394b823-5eb3-4eef-8db4-629d4e61d867"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "According to the Born rule, if a quantum state is written in the \
orthonormal eigenbasis of an observable as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
        StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
      "Ket"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7d7fe735-1841-4224-b836-10e4c10809e1"],
 ", then the probability of obtaining the eigenvalue corresponding to the \
eigenstate ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "30ddc430-cc25-4e92-b82e-066560f8f9eb"],
 " is given by the absolute square of the coefficient: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["P", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
     "Abs"], "2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c529a7e2-d9a2-4446-85ac-aa3b9c41ed10"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"3cc3e871-89a6-4634-823d-a308b8e65e83"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Given the state \[Psi] defined above, calculate the probability of \
obtaining ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[PlusMinus]"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "91936ebb-6906-4876-94a3-cd968ac4390d"],
 " if measuring Pauli-X:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2847905e-77aa-4e47-9abd-9e8c327cd5c0"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"x\\\", \
\\\"+\\\"]},\\\n\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"x\\\", \\\"-\\\"]},\
\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "newStateVectorX", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[77]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"0416fa20-7aed-46ef-82b0-c103868a5941"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Given the state \[Psi] defined above, calculate the probability of \
obtaining ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["y", "TI"], "\[PlusMinus]"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bcb768db-3c28-4df2-b4b0-8ca569877774"],
 " if measuring Pauli-Y:"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"4a024169-93f7-46d6-89d8-e81cc22ce8b0"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"right", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", "I"}], "}"}], "/", 
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"left", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"-", "I"}]}], "}"}], "/", 
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}]}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"newStateVectorY", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "right", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}], ",",
      " ", "\n", "   ", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "left", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}]}], 
    "}"}]}], ";"}], "\n", 
 RowBox[{"AssociationThread", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"y\\\", \
\\\"+\\\"]},\\\n\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\"", ",", " ", "\n", 
     "  ", "\"\<\\!\\(\\*TemplateBox[{\\nSubscriptBox[\\\"y\\\", \\\"-\\\"]},\
\\n\\\"Ket\\\"]\\)\>\""}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "newStateVectorY", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}], 
  "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[78]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"258047ea-2ff2-48c7-aaef-5db601dacde7"],

Cell["Expectation Values: Two Equivalent Computations", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"fdbe4ca2-8737-4671-bbf9-a7fe5127600c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Additionally, one can compute the expectation (mean) value of an \
observable. Given an operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["A", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7366447b-d963-4691-9051-6d5805108aad"],
 ", the expectation value in a normalized state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "ebe9b405-3a1c-4875-8bc8-c39114c6a269"],
 " is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Bra"], 
   StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c7f5478e-28e5-49dd-b7cd-f43c594ed507"],
 ", which can be also written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
     "Bra"], 
    StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
    TemplateBox[{
      StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
     "Ket"]}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[LeftAngleBracket]",
      SpanMaxSize->1], 
     StyleBox["A", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["\[RightAngleBracket]",
      SpanMaxSize->1]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"],
       LimitsPositioning->False], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
        StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["P", "TI"], 
        StyleBox["j", "TI"]]}]}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"],
       LimitsPositioning->False], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
        StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
       SuperscriptBox[
        TemplateBox[{
          SubscriptBox[
           StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
           StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
         "Abs"], "2"]}]}]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bad50967-2c35-48b0-95cf-3711559ed565"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["j", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d29386f9-95fe-423a-8a2b-66aa166b4f07"],
 " the eigenvalues and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["P", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["j", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "44234603-b95d-406d-b832-567fb9f058ba"],
 " the corresponding probability."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e854cd64-5a8a-4a6f-8916-85f9c26c72c3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute the expectation value of Pauli-X using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Bra"], 
   StyleBox["X", "TI"], 
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "bfee8a7c-ff90-4d11-9052-c7007e7a7c19"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"653154cb-ffdc-458c-91aa-ed6db4cea542"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "\[Psi]", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
   RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "1", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}], " ", "//",
   " ", "Chop"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[79]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"6c72c945-afee-447f-acbf-71a15db86faf"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute the expectation value of Pauli-X using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{" ", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]], " ", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
         StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
       "Abs"], "2"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "612e3758-4024-4b07-acbf-547176b8f4a6"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"22140027-f766-49fb-9bb7-d3995d4d8999"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], "}"}], " ", ".", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "newStateVectorX", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[80]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"11de025a-74ff-4b6d-8174-a8aa607ed5e3"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute the expectation value of Pauli-Y using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Bra"], 
   StyleBox["Y", "TI"], 
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a3821a34-cdc3-491b-8a33-b46047f1a02a"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"46d0eea3-c268-4c4c-8593-a163f009ada3"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", "\[Psi]", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
   RowBox[{"PauliMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}], " ", ".", " ", "\[Psi]"}], " ", "//",
   " ", "Chop"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[81]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"8fb05d9d-c9af-465a-ab9b-8f27a950d5b0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Compute the expectation value of Pauli-Y using ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{" ", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]], " ", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      TemplateBox[{
        SubscriptBox[
         StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
         StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
       "Abs"], "2"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "268425d1-2d5b-4322-823b-0f0a5a4fc13f"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ad2e246b-684f-4ab8-9762-332883150e58"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}], "}"}], " ", ".", " ", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Abs", "[", "newStateVectorY", "]"}], "^", "2"}]}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[82]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"edf61b6c-594f-4b6f-a0bf-080b47cb2b57"],

Cell["\<\
Before we move on to the next topic, let us summarize the most important \
points we have learned so far:\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c41767bc-4c8f-4156-9aaf-ada69ea0ad32"],

Cell["\<\
A pure state of a single qubit can be represented by a two-component vector {\
\[Alpha], \[Beta]}, where \[Alpha] and \[Beta] are complex numbers, also \
called as quantum amplitudes in a given basis.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7e155aca-b112-44c9-8836-d49bf02a8e9d"],

Cell["\<\
The above representation is always defined with respect to a chosen basis. \
Always keep that in mind: the components {\[Alpha], \[Beta]} tell you how the \
state is expanded in that particular basis\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"19faafb7-1758-4e1a-a4e2-f3f846bab7ef"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A normalized pure state of a single qubit can be fully described in its \
most general form by a two-component vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     StyleBox[
      RowBox[{"i", "\[Phi]"}], "TI"]], 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "93369328-e19f-482b-b24b-ddbeb3e26ec5"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
   StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], "\[LessEqual]", "\[Pi]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "669202ad-858a-482e-bf75-bc8427de97a5"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"0", "\[LessEqual]", 
   StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], "\[LessEqual]", "2", "\[Pi]"}]], "InlineFormula",
  
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d1b03b7e-9c00-4ddf-b579-d049cfde2913"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"c5b97adf-19bd-4cd5-ade9-3406494a20a2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Any normalized pure qubit state can be also represented as a point in \
three-dimensional space on the unit sphere, called the Bloch sphere. The \
corresponding Bloch vector is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Phi]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1]}], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    StyleBox["\[Theta]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0046e1da-4af0-412f-881e-dc7c0040385e"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"cd7c48f7-2665-48cc-8c81-0bfc45d5bdfd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "When an observable is measured, you should write the quantum state in the \
eigenbasis of that observable as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   TemplateBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Psi]", "TI"]},
    "Ket"], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    UnderscriptBox["\[Sum]", 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"],
     LimitsPositioning->False], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
      StyleBox["j", "TI"]], 
     TemplateBox[{
       SubscriptBox[
        StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
        StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
      "Ket"]}]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7e032ada-db87-47bf-8b7b-aa1130f5a4fe"],
 " where the index ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7e9386f8-8c24-4a1e-b065-2fc7f56a3a2a"],
 " runs over the eigenvalues, and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "33e373d3-6471-455d-b9ef-718ed0f75d1f"],
 " is the corresponding normalized eigenstate. Then the probability of \
obtaining outcome ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
   StyleBox["j", "TI"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c6340265-5956-4766-8a76-6f5d65a4344c"],
 " (i.e., the eigenvalue associated with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["v", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
   "Ket"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "935406cf-3a3e-461f-9ddd-bc16f910d2ba"],
 ") is given by the absolute square of the amplitude: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["P", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["j", "TI"]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    TemplateBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["c", "TI"], 
       StyleBox["j", "TI"]]},
     "Abs"], "2"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "34607a3d-739b-4691-9ccb-c4379979e823"],
 "."
}], "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9141041e-3d41-440c-85fb-72a91a02f368"],

Cell["\<\
There are infinitely many ways to choose a basis, and the choice depends on \
many factors, often computational convenience. In practice, eigenbases of \
observables are among the most commonly used bases.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fbc5fb32-2319-4d88-86cb-5ffb5f75b1bd"],

Cell["\<\
Note that the measurement description we discussed above is usually called as \
the projective measurement. Measurements can be beyond projective: positive \
operator-valued measure (POVM). We shall discuss them later.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2404fc76-04e1-4f73-8ee8-48e033de5652"],

Cell["\<\
Why Pure-State Vectors Aren\[CloseCurlyQuote]t Enough: The \
Stern\[Dash]Gerlach Experiment\
\>", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a54546bc-288d-4c13-8570-27d2fec631c4"],

Cell["\<\
Although many things can be computed using only state vectors and pure \
states, there are situations where this description is not sufficient. For \
example, in the famous Stern\[Dash]Gerlach experiment\[LongDash]where a beam \
of silver atoms is sent through an inhomogeneous magnetic field\[LongDash]the \
initial state of the atoms (even if we approximate each atom only by its \
electron spin) is typically an ensemble of states rather than a single pure \
state.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"968f6a76-5438-411f-9fe4-c2deec95ab6a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In the Stern\[Dash]Gerlach experiment, silver atoms are emitted from an \
oven and then pass through an external magnetic field with a strong gradient \
along a chosen direction. When a detector screen is placed at an appropriate \
distance, one observes two distinct spots, corresponding to the two possible \
outcomes (eigenvalues) of the spin observable along that direction, typically \
written as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], ".", 
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "7433446e-9f31-48ed-87b5-fc68c53b7abc"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f6bb5ddd-e264-4a4d-be2e-1b37f3991c72"],
 " is a unit vector specifying the measurement axis and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["S", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c7dd73a1-be4a-47ac-a85c-bcb4970b51e5"],
 " is the spin operator. The spin operator is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "1", "/", "2", 
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "0a9b8ea0-2bc3-40f8-9eaf-3ba7657ccf37"],
 " with ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", "{", 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["x", "TI"]]}], ",", 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["y", "TI"]], ",", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], 
     StyleBox["z", "TI"]], "}"}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "c33a2b33-6143-4284-b26d-b7f6830fa453"],
 " the Pauli operators."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"0af83c47-be7d-407e-af58-16eea16ba195"],

