Cell[TextData[{
 "An immediate consequence of the Zassenhaus formula is that we can always \
separate the identity part of an operator and ignore its physical effect, \
because the identity commutes with every operator. In other words: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"], "\|01d540", "+", 
      OverscriptBox[
       StyleBox["a", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}], ".", 
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"], "\|01d540"}]], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], ".", 
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "=", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    SubscriptBox[
     StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"]], 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], ".", 
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "e8fa0d08-1b1f-423c-8491-7d1c1383f97d"],
 ". The factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   SubscriptBox[
    StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "f65ec6d7-6d10-4672-a38e-01bd18e91493"],
 " is just an overall scalar (a global phase when ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SubscriptBox[
   StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "dce7b73e-5f79-4df7-adae-c900eeeab47a"],
 " is purely imaginary), so the physically relevant transformation is carried \
by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["a", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], ".", 
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "a3511236-a59f-420a-a5dc-aba1593f7ce7"],
 " alone."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"28aee11f-2c04-4f19-aa0c-9d9c1b8b9e55"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Verify that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"], "\|01d540"}]], ".", 
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], "=", 
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     SubscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "0"]], 
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "2a2b00d7-2723-4b41-a0af-d3ccd201dca8"],
 " for any generic vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["x", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "6752b796-94b5-47a6-bd68-65c585ebba4c"],
 ":"
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8d5f808f-9aa6-4fa5-ac5a-3fb60852c536"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"With", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"x", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"Array", "[", 
      RowBox[{"\[FormalV]", ",", " ", "2"}], "]"}]}], "}"}], ",", " ", "\n", 
   " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"MatrixExp", "[", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
        RowBox[{"\[FormalA]", ",", " ", "0"}], "]"}], " ", 
       RowBox[{"IdentityMatrix", "[", "2", "]"}]}], "]"}], " ", ".", " ", 
     "x"}], " ", "==", " ", "\n", "  ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"E", "^", 
      RowBox[{"Subscript", "[", 
       RowBox[{"\[FormalA]", ",", " ", "0"}], "]"}]}], " ", "x"}]}]}], 
  "]"}]], "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[180]:= ",ExpressionUUID->"7a742ebd-5383-469b-a968-58736d3c02d8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s recall what we have learned from these discussions. \
SU(2) is a set of 2\[Times]2 matrices closed under multiplication with an \
identity and inverses, and because the matrices vary smoothly with real \
parameters it is a Lie group. We then moved \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]inside\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] the group by looking at infinitesimal motions around \
the identity, which form the Lie algebra \|01d530\|01d532(2), the traceless \
anti-Hermitian 2\[Times]2 matrices. The Pauli matrices (multiplied by i or ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", 
   StyleBox["i", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "4d11dca2-b274-4116-874b-2d0712adaecd"],
 ", with a conventional 1/2 factor) provide a basis for this Lie algebra, and \
their commutators are encoded by the Levi-Civita symbol, mirroring the \
structure of 3D cross products. Using Pauli product identities, we showed how \
dot and cross products translate into operator products, and how \
exponentiating an \|01d530\|01d532(2) element produces a general SU(2) \
unitary of the form ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "/", "2", 
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["a", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}], ".", 
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "70485670-ab83-45c9-8a14-fc4a1811003c"],
 " with the closed-form cosine-sine expansion: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox[
     StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", 
       StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
       StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "/", "2", " ", 
       OverscriptBox[
        StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}], ".", 
      OverscriptBox[
       StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "=", 
    StyleBox["C", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["o", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["s", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], "\|01d540", "-", 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
    StyleBox["S", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["i", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], 
    StyleBox["[",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "/", "2"}], 
    StyleBox["]",
     SpanMaxSize->1], 
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}], ".", 
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b3cb0262-4c7d-472b-b9d7-339c78ad0c34"],
 ". Finally, we connected SU(2) actions on qubit states to SO(3) rotations of \
the Bloch vector under ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], "\[Rule]", 
    StyleBox["U", "TI"]}], ".", 
   StyleBox["\[Rho]", "TI"], ".", 
   SuperscriptBox[
    StyleBox["U", "TI"], "\[Dagger]"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d99a7b63-1423-4277-b5da-3313d24e2df6"],
 ", explained why the identity part of a generator only contributes an \
irrelevant global phase, and highlighted the double-cover subtlety: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  StyleBox["u", "TI"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "d7e64d98-6361-4be7-a670-734262a1c2a9"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{"-", 
   StyleBox["u", "TI"]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b33b4574-5a79-4c7f-87f9-c522bc2eb1b6"],
 " give the same Bloch-sphere rotation, so 2\[Pi] returns the Bloch vector \
but 4\[Pi] is needed to return the SU(2) element."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"13a04e1c-0cd7-4d34-bd40-21e9c1902227"],

Cell["Euler Angles: Decomposition of a Unitary Transformation", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"dac602ae-474c-4932-8e22-9a460424183f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Every physically relevant single-qubit transformation corresponds to a \
rotation of the Bloch sphere. So if unitaries are rotations, the next \
question is practical: how do we describe any rotation in a way that is easy \
to build? In SU(2), the transformation is described by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox[
   StyleBox["e", "TI"], 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", 
     StyleBox["i", "TI"], " ", 
     StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"], "/", "2", " ", 
     OverscriptBox[
      StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}], ".", 
    OverscriptBox[
     StyleBox["\[Sigma]", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]}]]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b58f8309-6367-4cbd-80c2-a0f422014b72"],
 " in Hilbert space, while in SO(3) it is given by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  RowBox[{
   SubscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalR]", 
    StyleBox["\[Alpha]", "TI"]], 
   StyleBox["(",
    SpanMaxSize->1], 
   OverscriptBox[
    StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"], 
   StyleBox[")",
    SpanMaxSize->1]}]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "acf622be-cf8b-4ef0-9da7-45bb0a2708bf"],
 " which is a rotation by angle \[Alpha] around the unit vector ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  OverscriptBox[
   StyleBox["n", "TI"], "\[RightVector]"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "43cfeac3-ef8b-479d-b84c-0b9d02dd5285"],
 " happening of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  SuperscriptBox["\:211d", "3"]], "InlineFormula",
  FontSize->0.9 Inherited,ExpressionUUID->
  "b6c33c7b-e773-4cce-911d-5c0dd03fd64d"],
 "."
}], "Text",ExpressionUUID->"53eee09b-9b8d-4f73-9a9a-0a03b11b4eb7"],

